						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Eni-to-invest-3-billion-in-Congo-s-oil-and-palm-oil-sector-Food-Plus-Biodiesel-project-to-employ-10-000-people" title="Eni to invest $3 billion in Congo's oil and palm oil sector; Food Plus Biodiesel project to employ 10,000 people " alt="link">Eni to invest $3 billion in Congo's oil and palm oil sector; Food Plus Biodiesel project to employ 10,000 people </a></h2>

	
					<p> Italy's largest industrial conglomerate, Eni, announced it will invest $3 billion in the Republic of Congo's hydrocarbon and palm oil biodiesel sector, generating an expected equity production of 150 million boe. A project focusing on the coproduction of food and biofuels will yield an estimated 10,000 formal jobs. The initiative is one in a series of recent bilateral and private investments in Central Africa's very large bioenergy potential. The Eni model combines the traditional activities of hydrocarbon exploration and production with sustainability and important initiatives with unconventional and renewable sources. Throughout the shared program with Eni, the Republic of Congo will maximise its own potential as a major energy producing country and become a benchmark in Africa in the tar sands and biofuels field, as a further benefit of food farming development. Source: Biopact, 20 May 2008.</p>
							<p><span class="date">30/06/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Eni-to-invest-3-billion-in-Congo-s-oil-and-palm-oil-sector-Food-Plus-Biodiesel-project-to-employ-10-000-people">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-project-to-boost-Africa-s-rice-production" title="New project to boost Africa's rice production " alt="link">New project to boost Africa's rice production </a></h2>

	
					<p> Japan, New Partnership for African Development, NEPAD and Alliance for Green Revolution in Africa have today launched a project to double Africa’s rice production in the next decade. Launched on Friday, the project aims to provide a variety of measures to increase rice production in the continent and will focus its efforts on getting high-yielding varieties of rice to smallholder farmers, improving soils, and supporting new agricultural research.Called the Coalition for African Rice Development (CARD), the project aims to drastically reduce Africa’s reliance on expensive rice imports through the development and distribution of the new resilient rice varieties for the continent’s smallholder farmers. According to the Africa Rice Center, the sufficiency ratio declined steadily over a 45-year period from 112% in 1961 to 61% in 2006, when the continent relied on the international rice market to satisfy about 39% of its rice consumption needs. The new initiative hopes to build on successful programs in countries like Uganda and Nigeria, where governments have cut rice imports in half over a few short years through investments in high yielding NERICA rice varieties that require little or no irrigation and are capable of growing in upland and lowland environments. Source: Henry Neondo, African Science News Service, 30 May 2008. </p>
							<p><span class="date">30/06/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/New-project-to-boost-Africa-s-rice-production">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Call-to-convert-Botswana-agricultural-stations-into-viable-research-centres" title="Call to convert Botswana agricultural stations into viable research centres" alt="link">Call to convert Botswana agricultural stations into viable research centres</a></h2>

	
					<p> An Agricultural Officer in Botswana has called for the upgrading of Agricultural Research Stations into institutions that would lead in recommending appropriate technologies for farming. Only about 0.7% of total Botswana land area is arable. Crop production is hampered by traditional farming methods, recurrent drought, erosion, and disease. Most of the land under cultivation is in the eastern region and the principal crops for domestic use are sorghum, maize, and millet. Agricultural research has been devoted to soil conservation, grazing experiments, and developing and distributing improved strains of grain. The construction of dams and the drilling of boreholes to tap underground water are continuing government programs. In early 1990, the government changed its official agricultural policy to emphasize the production only of those foodstuffs which can be raised economically. Source: African Science News Service, Botswana 31 May 2008. </p>
							<p><span class="date">30/06/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Call-to-convert-Botswana-agricultural-stations-into-viable-research-centres">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
