						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/With-UN-help-Africa-seeks-a-fair-share-of-green-development-cash" title="With UN help, Africa seeks a fair share of ‘green’ development cash" alt="link">With UN help, Africa seeks a fair share of ‘green’ development cash</a></h2>

	
					<p> With the global trade in carbon credits soon expected to top $100 billion annually, there is wide recognition that ways must to found to bring Africa, the least developed of the world’s continents, more fully into the market---and Africans are eager for this. Amid signs that global warming is damaging earth’s climate faster than expected, the UN is working with African governments and businesses to attract billions of dollars to the continent in “green” investments in cleaner energy and transport systems through a new financing body known as the Clean Development Mechanism. The opportunities are as great as the obstacles. Speaking on behalf of the African group of nations at Bali, the Nigeria government noted that adequate funding for climate change adaptation in Africa “remains inaccessible due to conditionality of co-financing… There is too much emphasis on seminars, workshops and needs assessment. For how long will our needs continue to be assessed?” In the meantime, the government said, “the suffering of our people continues.” Source: Michael Fleshman, African Science News Service, 6 June, 2008. </p>
							<p><span class="date">30/06/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/With-UN-help-Africa-seeks-a-fair-share-of-green-development-cash">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/South-African-scientists-to-benefit-from-European-biological-body" title="South African scientists to benefit from European biological body" alt="link">South African scientists to benefit from European biological body</a></h2>

	
					<p> South African scientists will gain access to the latest thinking in molecular biology research through an agreement announced today by the European Molecular Biology Organization (EMBO). The Government of the Republic of South Africa signed a cooperation agreement with the European Molecular Biology Conference (EMBC), the intergovernmental funding body for EMBO, allowing scientists from South Africa to participate in EMBO programmes and activities. Source: Clifford Akumu, African Science News Service, 5 June, 2008. </p>
							<p><span class="date">30/06/2008</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/South-African-scientists-to-benefit-from-European-biological-body">Read more...</a>
